glucose production","Stimulates glucagon release from pancreatic alpha cells","Blocks glucose absorption in the intestine","Stimulation of glucose-dependent insulin secretion","Increases insulin receptor sensitivity in muscle"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of GLP-1 analogues is \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulation of glucose-dependent insulin secretion\u003C/strong\u003E from pancreatic beta cells. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect inhibition of hepatic glucose production\u003C/strong\u003E:  GLP-1 analogues will indirectly affect hepatic glucose output through insulin and glucagon effects, but this is not their mechanism of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates glucagon release from pancreatic alpha cells\u003C/strong\u003E: GLP-1 analogues actually suppress rather than stimulate glucagon secretion, which helps reduce blood glucose levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks glucose absorption in the intestine\u003C/strong\u003E: this describes the mechanism of alpha-glucosidase inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases insulin receptor sensitivity in muscle\u003C/strong\u003E: this is the mechanism of insulin sensitisers like thiazolidinediones and metformin, not GLP-1 analogues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional actions of GLP-1 analogues include slowing gastric emptying, inhibiting inappropriate glucagon release, and reduced appetite. These medications are engineered to resist breakdown by dipeptidyl peptidase-4, giving them a longer duration of action than endogenous GLP-1. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1) analogues stimulate glucose dependent insulin secretion from pancreatic beta cells.","In addition to stimulation of glucose dependent insulins secretion, GLP-1 analogues suppress glucagon secretion, slow gastric emptying, and reduce appetite.","GLP-1 analogues are resistant to degradation by dipeptidyl peptidase-4, giving them a longer duration of action than endogenous GLP-1."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61836"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16895"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61836"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T08:06:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T08:07:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9585"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76327"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"